<section class="prose">
  <h1>The story</h1>
  <p class="updated">Two dads, one locked garden, and a fortnight.</p>

  <h2>A kid who couldn't message her friends</h2>
  <p>
    Eleven started because Paul's kid wanted to chat with her friends, and
    there was no good way to do it. Her friends' families had every kind of
    device, and Messages only really works if everyone buys Apple. The other
    apps wanted a phone number, an account, an age she didn't have, or a
    data trade no parent should sign a child up for.
  </p>
  <p>
    Think about that for a second. The simplest thing computers do —
    sending a few words to people you already know — and every mainstream
    option gates it behind a device brand, an identity, or an advertising
    business.
  </p>

  <h2>Two dads, same wall</h2>
  <p>
    Paul mentioned it to James, whose kids are younger and heading for the
    same wall. It resonated. Both of us have spent decades building software
    for the web, and both of us have watched the industry drift somewhere
    neither of us wants our kids to live: feeds engineered for compulsion,
    identities harvested by default, and staggering amounts of hardware and
    electricity spent keeping it all lit.
  </p>
  <p>
    We think a better version of this is possible. Not as a slogan — as a
    working app you can download today.
  </p>

  <h2>The inefficient factory</h2>
  <p>
    Here's the bet. AI is an expensive, energy-hungry factory — and like any
    factory, what matters is what comes out of it. A factory that builds
    solar panels earns its keep. So we pointed the inefficient factory at
    building ruthlessly <em>efficient</em> software: a messenger that's
    small, fast, private, and costs almost nothing to run.
  </p>
  <p>
    That's the Eleven model. Big tech never built this app because respecting
    people doesn't feed an advertising business, and a hand-built version
    wouldn't have been affordable. Built this way, it is. The same idea is
    written up more formally in
    <a href="https://11factor.org">The Eleven Factors</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Two weeks</h2>
  <p>
    In the first two weeks there was a working service, a web app, and
    native Mac and iPhone apps. Not mock-ups — the things you can get on
    <a href="/">the front page</a>. Encryption wasn't an add-on for later;
    it was there from the first message. And the way Eleven runs makes it
    potentially around thirty times more carbon-friendly than the way apps
    like this are usually built — the sums are on
    <a href="/planet/">the planet page</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The ambition is bigger than a family group chat: this design should
    scale to billions of people without the experience getting worse for
    any one of them, because every group lives in its own small, private
    space rather than one giant shared system. But it starts where it
    started — with a kid, her friends, and a chat worth having.
  </p>

  <h2>A co-op, not a corp</h2>
  <p>
    We don't want to build another company whose destiny is to be sold, and
    whose members are its inventory. Our intent is for Eleven to become a
    <strong>co-operative</strong> — owned by the people who use and run it,
    with open books and no exit to betray anyone toward. Until the
    paperwork exists, we act like it already does: see
    <a href="/openness/">the openness charter</a>.
  </p>

